  "text": "In this section, we present numerical experiments to demonstrate reduced communication behavior in an ETSE setting. We consider the stochastic systemẋ(t) = − tanh(x(t)) + 1 10 (t), where (t) is standard white noise. We assume x(0) = 6 and use the Euler-Maruyama method [CITATION_1] to sample from the system. We consider a fixed time horizon of T = 10 s and check according to the MIEDS algorithm different numbers of partitions of the state space. For the choice of λ = 0.01, we obtain m * = 2 and hence two local domains. We determine the switching point by evaluating the solution toẋ(t) = − tanh(x(t)) in t = 5 s. The local models are obtained with the aid of Taylor expansions and the MIEDS algorithm yields a linear function (k 1 = 1) within Ω 1 and a cubic polynomial (k 2 = 3) within Ω 2 .",
